        <bioghist id="ref46">
            <head>Biographical Note</head>
            <p>Benedict Arnold (1741-1801) served as a captain with the Connecticut militia and as colonel helped to capture Fort Ticonderoga, together with Ethan Allen and his troops in 1775. Severely injured in 1777, he was given command of the defense of Philadelphia in 1778. Accusations of abuse of power, overspending, and abrogating military directions led to a reprimand from General George Washington. Frustrated and thwarted, Arnold offered his services to the British and, while in command of West Point, made plans to turn it over to their forces. His plans were discovered based on interception of his letters, at which time Arnold joined the British and evaded capture. He fled to England in 1781 and died in London in 1801.</p>
        </bioghist>
        <scopecontent id="ref1">
            <head>Scope and Content</head>
            <p>The volume consists of a deed, and 41 letters (originals and typewritten transcripts) sent by Arnold and others to various recipients between 1772 and 1782.</p>
        </scopecontent>
        <accessrestrict id="ref10">
            <head>Access</head>
            <p>Letters in this volume have been microfilmed and will be presented to researchers in that format.</p>
        </accessrestrict>
        <custodhist id="ref11">
            <head>Provenance</head>
            <p>Presented by Samuel Verplanck Hoffman, President of the New-York Historical Society, May 4, 1911.</p>
        </custodhist>
        <arrangement id="ref12">
            <head>Arrangement</head>
            <p>The letters are arranged chronologically.</p>
        </arrangement>
        <relatedmaterial id="ref47">
            <head>Related Archival Material at New-York Historical Society</head>
            <p>Other letters of Arnold's are included in the Miscellaneous Manuscripts collection (MM Arnold), the Gates Papers, and the Duane Papers, among others. Researchers are encouraged to consult the card catalog in the Reading Room for complete information.</p>
        </relatedmaterial>
